Particles not only compose all matter, they are also responsible for how forces behave. One of the great achievements of physics has been the identification of four fundamental forces that form the basis of all other forces and interactions we can experience and see in our Universe. These basic forces are **gravity**, which prevents us drifting upwards towards the sky, and binds the planets and galaxies together; the **electromagnetic force**, which governs the flow of electricity in a cable, the magnetism pushing a compass' needle, and the light illuminating night; and two other forces, called the **weak** and **the strong nuclear forces**, which act at the atomic and nuclear level. The first is the force responsible for radioactivity and roughly one-half of the warmth produced in Earth's core, while the latter is what binds atoms' nuclei together, giving matter a stable form—without it, we wouldn't be here right now! We know today that the last three forces listed above are carried out by particles: the intangible and massless photon is the carrier of the electromagnetic force; two particles—cryptically called W and Z—, carry out the weak nuclear force; and the particle called gluon is the bearer of the strong nuclear force.
// Particle physicists study the nature of such carrier particles as well, and how they interact with the other particles.

Studying these basic elements and forces which compose the Universe around us means understanding the innermost mechanisms which govern the tangible part of the Universe we all live in, or in other words, understanding what composes our own lives.


### Natural sources of particles

[Aside]
  [Recirc slug:parametricSlug /]
[/Aside]

At the end of the 19[sup]th[/sup] century, J.J. Thomson discovered the first fundamental particle: the electron, one of the building blocks of the atom. The discovery of the electron marked the beginning of particle physics. Then, at the beginning of the 20[sup]th[/sup] century, scientists observed that particles were not only part of the structure of matter, but they were also produced in natural phenomena.

Many elements are naturally radioactive. One of the most well known is Uranium, commonly used today as fuel in nuclear power plants. In the past, clock-makers used Radium and Tritium to make glowing-in-the-dark clock-hands. These elements have unstable structures, which cause them to spontaneously emit particles as byproducts of their internal readjustment—what gives them their glow. Depending on the characteristics of the radioactive atom, different types of particles are emitted: electrons, photons, or the so-called "alpha" particles (two protons and two neutrons bound together). Such radioactive elements are naturally present in small quantities in our soil, and were the object of study by particle physics pioneers, such as Henri Becquerel, and Marie and Pierre Curie.

Particles from the cosmos continuously breach the atoms of the Earth's upper atmosphere. In these collisions, other particles are produced and travel towards our planet's surface. Many of them get trapped in subsequent collisions, some of them reach the ground, while others traverse the Earth and continue traveling undisturbed. These particles are called "cosmic rays". Among them, we find photons and electrons, but also muons — a sort of heavy electron — and positrons — the equivalent anti-matter of the electron. Cosmic rays are harmless to us: humanity has evolved in such an environment, and the human body is accustomed to such "particle showers."

Natural sources of particles were the focus of the first experiments in particles physics, and since, many other particles have been discovered studying this initial set, e.g., the positron and muon.

### How do we observe and study particles?

Particles are the smallest known objects in the Universe, and are intangible like light. So how can scientists observe, study, and most astonishingly, manipulate them?

Particles can't really be "seen," because seeing something involves sending a beam of visible light toward the thing we want to see and then receiving some light bouncing back from the thing to our eyes. But particles are so small that no visible light bounces back, even when using the most powerful of microscopes. Therefore, we have to find other ways to "see" particles.

All particles behave differently when passing through matter. Electrons and photons, for example, rapidly lose their energy by continuously coliding with other material atoms until they get trapped. Protons travel through matter almost unnoticed until they are close to the end of their journey. At that moment, they lose all their energy in a burst, and immeidately stop. Muons, on the other hand, can travel through layers and layers of any material, or even through hundreds of meters of solid rock, without losing much of their energy. This is why scientists build underground labs, buried deep under mountains, for example, the [a href:"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laboratori_Nazionali_del_Gran_Sasso"]Gran Sasso laboratory in Italy[/a], to try to shield sensitive scientific experiments from cosmic muons coming from the sky. Neutrinos, another particle, interact weakly with all other objects: they pass through entire planets without stopping.

