### How do we accelerate particles, and how do accelerators work?

Electromagnetic fields influence the speed and trajectories of charged particles. An electromagnetic field can always be divided into two distinct components: an electric field and a magnetic field. The force exerted by the field on a charged particle is the so-called "Lorentz force":

[Equation display:true]
  F=q[E+(v\times B)]
[/Equation]

In the above formula, [Equation]q[/Equation] is the charge of the particle and [Equation]v[/Equation] its velocity, [Equation]E[/Equation] is the electric field, and [Equation]B[/Equation] is the magnetic field. Thus, for a given electric and magnetic field, the particle experiences a force [Equation]F[/Equation] from the field depending on its charge and speed. But what if we could control the fields [Equation]E[/Equation] and [Equation]B[/Equation]?

If we rewrite the formula by isolating the velocity of the particle and the radius of the bending of its trajectory, we find this:

[Equation display:true]
  v = \sqrt{ \frac{2q(V_2-V_1)}{m}}
[/Equation]

[Equation display:true]
  r = \frac{mv}{qB} \sin\theta
[/Equation]

We now have two expressions: the first describes the velocity of a particle, [Equation]v[/Equation], given the potential difference of the electric field, while the second describes the radius of the curvature of the particle's trajectory, [Equation]r[/Equation], given the speed of the particle and the strength of the magnetic field. Notice that only the electic field [Equation]E[/Equation] appears in the first formula, which means that the velocity [Equation]v[/Equation] only depends on the strength of the electric field, while only the magnetic field [Equation]B[/Equation] appears in the second equation. Therefore, we can use an electric field to accelerate a charged particle, and a magnetic field to bend its trajectory and steer it.

[Aside]
The particle in the diagram has been **drasitically slowed down**. In reality, the particle would instantly fly out of the page, since an electron put in a small accelerator (say, of 10 meters) and pushed by an electric field (say, of 100 Volts), will be accelerated to a speed of about 6 million meters per second—that is almost 22 million km/h!
That speed, while fast on its own, is still much slower than the speed of light—the fastest possible speed in Nature—, which is about 1 billion km/h!

Also, notice how much more energy is needed to push a proton, which has the same electric charge as an electron, but contains a much higher mass. You have to set the highest Volts value to make it move!
