Using these two principles, physicists started building *particle accelerators*. By using accelerating modules one after another, we can build so-called *"linear accelerators"*. These have limit on their maximal attainable energyby the number of accelerating modules, in other words, the total length of the accelerator. On the other hand, by using accelerating and bending modules, we can build *"circular accelerators"*: particles are injected into a ring composed of bending modules, which force particles to move in a circular path, while one accelerating module pushes the particles each time they pass through by. After a given amount of turns, the particles attain their maximum energy and can be used for experiments.

Physicists use these accelerators to study the basic characteristics of particles, but it quickly became clear that these accelerators could have many applications to industry and other scientific fields.

The old television set was based on the cathode-ray tube, which is nothing more than a compact particle accelerator! Electrons are produced at one end by applying an electric field which accelerates them, causing them to fly towards the other end of the tube, which is covered by a layer of phosphorescent material that becomes luminescent when hit by an electron. The trajectory of the electrons is bent by using a variable magnetic field, which force them to hit the luminescent screen at different points. By modulating the intensity of the magnetic field, the electron beam "paints" an image on the screen.

