So how much energy can a particle traveling in an accelerator attain?

Particles in a linear accelerator gain energy by passing through a series of accelerating modules, each of them propelling the particle further. The limit of the amount of energy particles can obtain only depends on the number of the accelerating modules—the longer the accerleator, the more energy attained. That is why accelerators are so long and cost so much! On the other hand, circular accelerators only contain one accelerating module: they accelerate particles at high energy by pushing them through the electrical field many times. Every time a particle passes through the single accelerating module, it gets a kick which gives it a bit more kinetic energy. In principle, there is no limit to the number of times a particle can be pushed through the accelerating section of a circular collider. However, in practice after a certain point the energy leaks due to many different physical effects that are larger than the kick received by the electric field. At that point, the circular accelerator has attained its energy limit due to its construction and design.

Circular accelerators can be further divided into two main groups: "cyclotrons," which were the first to be invented around 1930, and "synchrotrons." The former are commonly used in hospitals today. The latter are used in machines for cutting-edge research in particle physics, such as the [a href:"https://home.cern/science/accelerators/large-hadron-collider"]Large Hadron Collider ("LHC")[/a] at [a href:"https://home.cern/"]CERN[/a].

